{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In another life I was a Jew in a concentration camp. It was more horrible than you can imagine and, in the end, I was burned alive. I was sent to Burchenwhul in a jack-booted raid in the middle of one swampy night. Both me and the love of my life were snatched from our beds and eventually forced onto a train to the death camp. After living a loving life, it ended in the bottom of a furnace in excruciating pain.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 But that was a lifetime ago. I don\u8217't remember these things, but they happened nonetheless. The experience burned into my soul. In a way, this kind of experience ends up informing the rest of your existence. This time around things are a bit different, but life always seems to find a way to resonate with the unconscious. For example, the guards that made the end of my last life a living hell are now my best friends.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Of course, I didn\u8217't know who they were in that other life and, as young children do, I made friends with those whose personalities meshed with mine. They also had no way of knowing the seemingly unending torture they inflicted to an entire camp of desperate Jews, but I imagine that experience is also burned into their souls as well. The universe\u8217's idea of divine retribution I guess.\par}
